              <div class="post-preview">
		
		                     		  <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
		  <ol>		    

		    <li>Learn the angular solutions for the Schrodinger equation corresponding to the Hydrogen atom. </li>
		    <li>Learn to interpret angular probabilities for the Hydrogen atom. </li>
		 
		  </ol><br><br>
Last session we learnt that the angular component of the wavefunctions for the Hydrogen atom are given by the combination $\Theta_{\ell, m_{\ell}}\Phi_{m_{\ell}}$ which are known as the <b>spherical harmonics</b>
                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spherical_harm0.png" %}" width="800"></center><br>
Let us plot an examples, say  <a href="https://www.wolframalpha.com/input?i=PolarPlot%5B3+cos%28theta%29%5E2-1%5D" target="_blank" style="color:blue;">  $\Theta_{\ell=2, m_{\ell}=0}$. </a>

		    <h3>But what $(\ell,m_{\ell})$ mean?</h3>
		    Let us start by remembering that   <em> angular momentum $L={\bf p}\times {\bf r}$  is a vector perpendicular to the orbital plane.</em><br><br> Do you remember the right-hand rule?. <br><br>
		   Say a particle is moving on a circular orbit on the $x-y$ plane, what is the direction of the angular momentum vector. 
		    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $x$</li>
		   <li> $y$</li>
		    <li> $z$</li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
			<br><br>
			<center>   <img src="{% static "img/angular_momentun.png" %}" width="500"></center><br>
			 <center>   <img src="{% static "img/angular_momemtum_2.png" %}" width="500"></center><br><br>

Remember that an spinning object with changing angular momentum vector, can still have constant angular momentum norm (size, length) as well as constant angular momentum projection on one of the axis (say $z$.)<br><br>     
			 
                    It turns out that the combined polar and azimuthal equations are the square of the angular momentum operator, and which is quantized by the integer $\ell$, whereas the integer $m_{\ell}$ corresponds to the quantization of projection of angular momenta in the $z$ direction:<br><br> <center> $ \boxed{L_z=\hbar m_{\ell}} $ and $ \boxed{|L|=\hbar\sqrt{\ell(\ell+1)}}$.</center>
			 <br>
What does this two last relations mean to you, physically? <br><br>
			 
			   Can $m_{\ell}$ be bigger that |L|? _______ <b>(yes, no)</b>.<br><br>
			   

                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spin_quant0.png" %}" width="500"></center>
                    <br><br>
		    All in all, the angular piece of the wavefunction for the Hydrogen atom, is determined by two <b>quantum numbers</b>, $\ell$ and $m_{\ell}$, which are given by,
		    $$\ell=0,1,2,\cdots$$ and $$m_{\ell}=0,\pm 1,\pm 2\cdots\pm\ell\,,\quad {\rm or}\quad -\ell\leq m_{\ell}\leq \ell\,.\quad{\rm With}\quad m_{\ell}\in \mathbb{Z}\,.$$ 
		    Which determine the angular momentum as,
		    $ L_z=\hbar m_{\ell} $ and $ |L|=\hbar\sqrt{\ell(\ell+1)}.$
Say $\ell=2$, then, 
		    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $ m_{\ell}=-1, 0, 1$</li>
		   <li> $ m_{\ell}=-2, 0, 2$</li>
		    <li> $ m_{\ell}=-3, 0, 3$</li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
		    
		    Notice that classically, the angular momentum will be determined by three quantities, say $(L_x,L_y,L_z)$, however quantum mechanically we only need two $(\ell,m_{\ell})$ due to the Heisenberg's uncertainty principle.   
                 
                  
			<h3>Angular probabilities</h3>
			Before look into the radial component, let us take a look at the angular probabilities for an electron of the Hydrogen atom. <br>
			First thing to notice is that, since the probability densities are given by the square of the wave function,  the $\phi$ dependence is always constant (=1).
			<!-- Even though we are considering a system with spherical symmetry, and at a given angular momentum $\ell$ the total probability would be angular independent, as it should be for a spherical symmetric system, it is important to have understand the angular dependence in order to gain a better understanding of the total wavefunction (among other things, in practical experiments, we are able to distinguish diferent angular components, by sort of breaking the spherical symmetry by applying an interaction). -->
			<br><br>
			
			<center>   <img src="{% static "img/angular_prob1_0.png" %}" width="550"> </center>
<br><br>
Lets take as an example the angular probability for an electron at $\ell=2$ and $m_{\ell}=0$, what of the following is the most accurate statement?  
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> Electron's orbit is most likely on $x-y$ plane. </li>
		   <li> Electron's orbit is most likely on $x-z$ plane. </li>
		   <li> Electron's angular momentum is most likely $(0,0,|L|). </li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
			<br><br>
			The lobes represent the probability for the "location" of the electron's orbit, as seeing from the angular momentum. 

			<center> <img src="{% static "img/angular_prob2_0.png" %}" width="370"></center>

			<h2>Next: "Radial solutions for the Hydrogen atom.</h2>
			
